A lot of the times when old people have "a fall" where they suffer a hip fracture actually the hip fracture *precedes* the fall. Everyone assumes the fall causes the fracture but often the hip just breaks spontaneously because it has become too frail and the old person fall down.

It's why the standard safetyism approach of putting old people in essentially a padded cell room where they can't slip and fall is not that productive and the Japanese high dose 45 mg K2 supplement protocol to prevent osteoporosis and strengthen bones makes very much more sense.

My dad's favorite books are The Good Soldier Svejk and Catch-22 and I hadn't read the second but knew it was about army stuff and just thought he enjoyed "military humor" but now I'm actually going through it and it's literally just American Svejk.
